title: For Sale:  Gary Reeder Improved #6 .44 Mag custom revolver
postcontent:
Gary Reeder Improved #6 in .44 Magnum. This was Reeder's limited run of a magnum #5 (his #5 Improved came in .44 Special and he differentiated the Magnums by calling them a #6). This is not to be confused with his current "New #6," which is a stretch frame revolver. Reeder made these on his own, proprietary main frame rather than customizing an existing gun, such as a Ruger. This one is serial number 11. I bought it from Reeder when he handled the estate of the original owner a few years ago. I purchased it to make comparisons to TLA #5s firsthand for my book research. It also helped that the SN matched my very first TLA, so I planned on keeping it and hunting with it and the TLA. I really don't need it, though, and need to get my money back out of it.

It has the optional octagon barrel and is stainless steel, with Reeder's vapor-honed finish on most of the gun and a high polish stainless finish on the small parts. The polish is mirror bright and in some of the pictures, looks weird because it is reflecting the environment (for instance, look at the hammer side in the full view of the left side of the gun - looks dark because it is reflecting something, but it is mirror polished). The gun has been shot and has a turn line from the New Model-style action he uses. Also has a couple light marks from handling and use, but is in very nice condition. Lock-up is extremely tight, with no endshake and just a tiny touch of sideplay (and I mean tiny - it is as tight as most of my TLAs and other customs). The action is very smooth and the trigger pull is just heavy enough for use, but light enough for accurate shooting. It is a bit creepy, but is still a very nice trigger. I never got around to shooting the gun, but the other Reeders I have owned have been very accurate and I expect this one is no different.

The stocks are ivory colored corian, which is a rugged, utilitarian stock material that also looks good. Not as nice as real ivory, for sure, but it does go well with the satin stainless finish.

Comes with the Reeder box and Reeder gun sock, but I didn't get any paperwork with it. Don't know if anyone got paperwork with these, for that matter.

If I recall correctly, this gun cost well over $2200, including options, when Reeder sold them back around 2005 or 2006. I paid less than the original bill, I remember that. Looking to get $2250 shipped fully insured from my FFL dealer to yours. Or, $2,175 face to face in Hickory, NC. I really need cash, but will entertain trade offers if I feel I can sell them either easier or for more than my price on this one. My price is firm - I'm looking to break even on it and it is well priced for what it is.

Also includes the original case and papers, five 40 cal mags and a serpa-style holster.  I also threw in the Apex RAM to give it a better reset.

*IMPORTANT- Regarding Rebuild Kits*
A "REBUILD KIT" is a complete magazine that has been disassembled into parts. 

It contains all the original parts of the magazine that have been taken apart before being shipped into Colorado to comply with state and local laws.  I do not remove any parts of the rebuild kit before we ship to customers. 
Rebuild kits are not to be used to assemble a new high capacity magazine which would be in violation of local or state law. These rebuild kits are intended to rebuild a legally owned pre-ban magazine or for assembling a 10 round magazine pursuant to local or state law.

For example: You can take your rebuild kit from Colorado to Arizona, assemble it, use it, and take it apart before you return to Colorado. Many of our customers are competition shooters who reside in CO but travel the country shooting and require rebuild kits for competition. Others attend weapon training facilities in other states where they are legally allowed to assemble and use rebuild kits as magazines. title: For Sale:  Cooper Arms 54 Colt 175th Anniversary 308
postcontent:
This is a brand new in box Cooper Model 54 "Colt 175th Anniversary" edition bolt action rifle chambered for .308 Winchester. It is one of only 175 produced to commemorate the 175th anniversary of Samuel Colt's first gun, the Colt Paterson. The Paterson was the first commercial repeating firearm recognizable as a revolver, employing a revolving cylinder with multiple chambers and a single stationary barrel.

This rifle features beautiful engraving on the receiver, magazine floor plate, and part of the barrel. The Colt logo on the receiver and the rampant Colt on the floor plate are 24k gold plated. The metals are all blued, contrasting nicely with the checkered AA Claro Walnut stock. The grip cap is engraved with "Limited Edition, 1 of 175."
